\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Lucas Benedičič was born on December 12, 1977 in Buenos Aires, Argentina.
 After enrolling as a grade student at the University of Buenos Aires, he
 attended and completed the first 4 years of the undergraduate programme
 in computer sciences at the Faculty of Exact and Natural Sciences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After moving to Slovenia in 2002, he enrolled the University of Ljubljana,
 Faculty of Computer and Information Science, where he graduated in 2007
 with the work titled »Application development using open-source technologies«.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In September 2007, he started his postgraduate studies at the University
 of Primorska, Faculty of Mathematics, Natural Sciences and Information
 Technologies, after enrolling the Masters' study programme for computer
 sciences.
 He graduated in 2009 with the work titled »Optimization of Common Pilot
 Channels in UMTS Networks«.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Towards the end of 2007, he was awarded a scholarship for continuing postgraduat
e studies in Slovenia.
 The award was received after winning an open contest of problem solving,
 organized by Halcom, d.d.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In fall 2009, he enrolled in the PhD program entitled “Information and Communica
tion Technologies” under the supervision of Assistant Professor Peter Korošec,
 at the Jožef Stefan International Postgraduate School in Ljubljana, Slovenia.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In November 2009 he became a junior researcher from industry, funded by
 the European Union through the European Social Fund.
 During this period he is holding working positions at Telekom Slovenije,
 d.d., in research and development within the Radio Network Department, and
 at the Jožef Stefan Institute, in the Computer Systems Department.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 2011 he attended and successfully completed the summer institute »Scientific
 Computing in the Americas: the challenge of massive parallelism«, organized
 by the Pan-American Advanced Studies Institute, Boston University.
 The focus of the institute was on advanced topics of theory and programming
 of massively parallel processors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In early 2012, he received an invitation to work as a visiting researcher
 at the Nagasaki Advanced Computer Center (NACC) at the University of Nagasaki,
 Japan.
 His joint research work at NACC is to be completed by the end of 2012.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
His research interests include combinatorial and numerical optimization,
 mostly applied to optimization problems in the area of 3G radio networks,
 metaheuristic algorithms, parallel and GPU computing.
 Over the last few years, he has presented his research work at several
 international conferences and workshops in the areas of evolutionary computatio
n, optimization and parallel computing.
\end_layout

